The input parameters for our models are the PNS mass  $(M_{\mathrm{NS}} / M_{\odot} \in [1.4,2.1])$ , the total neutrino luminosity  $(L_{
u} \in [3	imes 10^{52},1.2	imes 10^{53}]\mathrm{erg s}^{- 1})$ , and the wave luminosity as a fraction of total neutrino luminosity  $(L_{w} / L_{
u} \in [10^{- 5},10^{- 2}])$ . We also examine the impact of different wave frequencies in the range of  $10^{2}$  to  $10^{4}\mathrm{s}^{- 1}$ . We assume that the neutrinos have equal luminosities in all flavors, a zero chemical potential Fermi- Dirac spectrum, and the average electron neutrino energy is fixed at  $12\mathrm{MeV}$  as measured at the surface of the PNS. The average electron antineutrino energy is chosen such that the equilibrium electron fraction of the wind,  $Y_{e,\mathrm{eq}} = \lambda 
u_{e} / (\lambda 
u_{e} + \lambda  ar{
u}_{e})$ , takes a target value (see Qian & Woosley 1996), where  $\lambda 
u_{e}$  and  $\lambda  ar{
u}_{e}$  are the electron neutrino and antineutrino capture rates, respectively. We primarily consider  $Y_{e,\mathrm{eq}} = 0.48$ , unless otherwise noted. Relativistic corrections are included in the neutrino capture rates as in Thompson et al. (2001).
